{
  "answer": "Surah Al-Ma'un 107:4-6 issues a severe warning to those who are neglectful of their prayers and perform them merely to make a show of their deeds [1]. This insincere outward display characterizes hypocrites who lack a true understanding of the Hereafter and its impending judgment [2]. \n\nSurah Al-Kahf 18:110 firmly anchors the necessity of absolute sincerity by commanding that whoever hopes to meet their Lord must perform righteous work and never associate anyone else in the worship of God [3]. \n\nOther primary ayat further reinforce the scriptural prohibition of ostentation:\n*   **Surah Al-Baqarah 2:264:** Commands believers not to ruin their charitable deeds by spending wealth solely to be seen by people, linking this behavior directly to a lack of belief in God and the Last Day [4].\n*   **Surah An-Nisa 4:38:** Condemns those who spend their wealth just to be seen by others, stating that they believe neither in God nor the Last Day and have Satan as an evil companion [5]. \n\nAdditionally, authentic narrations warn of the physical and spiritual consequences of this sin, noting that on the Day of Resurrection, anyone who used to pray and prostrate merely out of ostentation or fear of people will be unable to bow before God, as He will make their backs rigid and stiff [6].",
  "conversation_id": "b75c54d4-0ca8-4686-8f68-eef116d359e6",
  "turn_number": 1,
